      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 9-year-old boy is brought to a pediatric outpatient department with a 5-month history of rectal bleeding, characterized by fresh blood clearly visible on the stool. The boy reports no significant constipation, vomiting, diarrhea, or weight loss. His diet is typical for his age, and he is growing appropriately. On examination, his abdomen is soft with mild tenderness on the right side, and stool is palpable in the descending colon. A sentinel skin tag is observed in the perianal area, but no fissures are present. Complete blood count (CBC) is within normal range, and both X-ray and histopathological examination (HPE) of the bowel show no abnormalities. Considering the clinical presentation, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9099284",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33037,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Meckel’s diverticulum</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Meckel’s diverticulum </strong>is a <strong>congenital condition </strong>that can cause <strong>painless rectal bleeding, </strong>which may be <strong>fresh and mixed with stool</strong>. The <strong>presence of a sentinel skin tag </strong>could be associated with <strong>underlying rectal bleeding. Normal growth</strong>, <strong>absence of systemic symptoms </strong>like <strong>weight loss</strong>, <strong>vomiting</strong>, and <strong>diarrhea</strong>, and <strong>normal bowel habits make constipation and inflammatory bowel disease less likely</strong>. Campylobacter enterocolitis typically presents with diarrhea and systemic symptoms, which are not reported in this case.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;<strong>A. Constipation:</strong> Could cause <strong>rectal bleeding due to anal fissures</strong>, but the patient denies significant constipation, and no fissure was found on examination.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;<strong>B. Inflammatory bowel disease:</strong> Usually presents with diarrhea, weight loss, and systemic symptoms, which are not observed in this boy.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;<strong>C. Campylobacter enterocolitis:</strong> This typically <strong>presents with diarrhea, fever, and abdominal pain</strong>, which are not consistent with this patient’s history.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Meckel’s diverticulum </strong>is a <strong>congenital abnormality of the small intestine </strong>and can present with symptoms such as <strong>painless rectal bleeding</strong>, <strong>abdominal pain</strong>, and occasionally <strong>intestinal obstruction</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:</u></strong> <strong>Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No 1854-1874.</strong></span></p>",
