      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">During a routine visit, a mother expresses concern about her 6-month-old child&#39;s frequent vomiting, which seems to be non-pathological upon examination. The child appears otherwise healthy with no detectable abnormalities. To address the mother&#39;s concerns and provide reassurance, you explain that this is a common occurrence in infants and not indicative of a serious condition. What would you identify as the most common cause of this vomiting in an otherwise healthy infant?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4492432",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33038,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">.<strong> A) Aerophagia</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Aerophagia </strong>is the <strong>most common cause of vomiting in children</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Aerophagia</strong>, <strong>hydrophagia</strong>, and <strong>milkophagia </strong>are conditions related to <strong>swallowing behaviors</strong>, each involving the <strong>excessive intake of a particular substance</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>B. Hydrophagia</strong>: Hydrophagia refers to <strong>excessive drinking of water, </strong>which is not typically associated with frequent vomiting in infants unless it leads to water intoxication, which is rare and usually not a common cause of vomiting in this age group.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>C. Milkophagia</strong>: &quot;Milkophagia&quot; is not a recognized medical term. However, <strong>excessive milk intake or overfeeding can lead to vomiting in infants</strong>, but it is less common compared to aerophagia, especially in the absence of other symptoms like poor weight gain or discomfort during feeding.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>D. Esophageal atresia:</strong> Esophageal atresia is a <strong>congenital condition where the esophagus does not develop properly</strong>, leading to a <strong>gap or blockage</strong>. It typically presents with difficulty swallowing, choking, and regurgitation of feedings shortly after birth, rather than at 6 months of age. Additionally, there would likely be abnormalities seen on examination or imaging studies.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Aerophagia </strong>refers to the <strong>swallowing of air</strong>, which can <strong>occur during feeding or crying in infants</strong>, leading to <strong>frequent episodes of vomiting</strong>. This is a common and benign cause of vomiting in infants, especially during the first few months of life when their feeding patterns are still developing.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref - Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition Chapter 368, Page No- 8087</span></span></strong></p>",
